The JSE, which benefited from a weakening rand on Monday and Tuesday, looked set to stumble on Wednesday, judging by markets trading ahead of its opening. Sydney’s S&P/ASX 200 index was down 1% and Tokyo’s Nikkei 225 index lost 0.54%, suffering from the dollar weakening on reports US President Donald Trump intends to replace Federal Reserve chairwoman Janet Yellen with his National Economic Council director Gary Cohn. The dollar was also rattled by a fresh scandal in Trump’s alleged help from the Kremlin in the 2016 presidential race. Trump’s son Donald Trump Jr posted e-mails on his Twitter account revealing a meeting with a Russian lawyer who had promised to share damaging information on Hillary Clinton. The rand was trading at R13.54/$, R15.55/€ and R17.40/£ at 7am. The extent to which South African consumers remained gloomy will be revealed when consumer confidence data are released. The First National Bank-sponsored survey by Stellenbosch University’s Bureau for Economic Research is due for release at 1pm. A poll of economists done by Trading Economics found consumer confidence index for the first quarter of 2017 was expected to have improved slightly to negative 8.4 points from negative 10 in the fourth quarter of 2016.